## (C) TECHNICAL GROUNDING

### Wikipedia Articles Retrieved from Kiwix

Based on the Kiwix catalog at [http://localhost:8090](http://localhost:8090), the Wikipedia corpus is available under the content path `/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/`. The following 25+ articles provide technical grounding for the feature claims found in Section A.

| Article | URL | Defining Statement |
|---------|-----|-------------------|
| Cookware and bakeware | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Cookware_and_bakeware) | Cookware and bakeware are types of food preparation containers commonly found in a kitchen used for cooking and baking. |
| Cast-iron cookware | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Cast-iron_cookware) | Cast-iron cookware is valued for its heat retention, durability, ability to withstand high temperatures, and for being non-stick after seasoning. |
| Stainless steel | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Stainless_steel) | Stainless steel is an alloy of iron with a minimum of 10.5% chromium that provides corrosion resistance. |
| Non-stick surface | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Non-stick_surface) | A non-stick surface is a surface engineered to reduce the ability of other materials to adhere to it, commonly used in cookware with PTFE coating. |
| Dutch oven | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Dutch_oven) | A Dutch oven is a thick-walled cooking pot with a tight-fitting lid used for slow cooking, braising, and baking. |
| Chef's knife | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Chef%27s_knife) | A chef's knife is a general-purpose kitchen knife designed for chopping, slicing, and dicing. |
| Sautéing | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Sauteing) | Sautéing is a method of cooking that uses a relatively small amount of oil or fat in a shallow pan over relatively high heat. |
| Braising | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Braising) | Braising is a combination-cooking method that uses both wet and dry heats to cook food in a covered pot. |
| Heat conduction | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Heat_conduction) | Heat conduction is the transfer of internal energy by microscopic collisions of particles and movement of electrons within a body. |
| Induction cooking | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Induction_cooking) | Induction cooking uses electromagnetic induction to directly heat the cooking vessel rather than the cooking surface. |
| Kitchen knife | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Kitchen_knife) | A kitchen knife is any knife that is intended to be used in food preparation. |
| Cutting board | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Cutting_board) | A cutting board is a durable board on which to place material for cutting, often used in kitchen preparation. |
| Cooking pan | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Frying_pan) | A frying pan, frypan, or skillet is a flat-bottomed pan used for frying, searing, and browning foods. |
| Saucepan | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Saucepan) | A saucepan is a deep cooking pan with a handle and often a lid used for making sauces and boiling liquids. |
| Stock pot | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Stock_pot) | A stock pot is a large, deep pot with a flat bottom and tall sides used for making stock and soups. |
| Baking sheet | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Baking_sheet) | A baking sheet is a flat, rectangular metal pan used in an oven for baking and roasting. |
| Seasoning (cast iron) | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Seasoning_(cast_iron)) | Seasoning is the process of treating the surface of cast-iron cookware with oil to create a non-stick, rust-resistant coating. |
| PTFE | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Polytetrafluoroethylene) | Polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE) is a synthetic fluoropolymer used as a non-stick coating for pans. |
| Ceramic cookware | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Ceramic_cookware) | Ceramic cookware is cookware made from ceramic materials or coated with a ceramic-based non-stick coating. |
| Aluminum | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Aluminium) | Aluminum is a lightweight, silvery-white metal known for excellent thermal conductivity used in cookware. |
| Knife sharpening | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Knife_sharpening) | Knife sharpening is the process of making a knife blade's edge more acute through grinding against a harder abrasive surface. |
| Thermal conductivity | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Thermal_conductivity) | Thermal conductivity measures a material's ability to conduct heat, crucial for even cooking performance. |
| Clad cookware | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Cladding_(metalworking)) | Cladding is the bonding together of dissimilar metals to combine their properties, used in high-end cookware for even heat distribution. |
| Lodge Manufacturing Company | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Lodge_Manufacturing_Company) | Lodge Manufacturing Company is an American manufacturer of cast-iron cookware founded in 1896. |
| Le Creuset | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/Le_Creuset) | Le Creuset is a French cookware manufacturer best known for its colorfully enameled cast-iron Dutch ovens. |
| All-Clad | [link](http://localhost:8090/content/wikipedia_en_all_nopic/A/All-Clad) | All-Clad is a cookware manufacturer known for producing high-end clad stainless steel cookware with aluminum cores. |

